Clustering

Certainly we face clustering in most of the situations in daily challenges related to data. Clustering is an attempt to structure the objects depending on the specific rule defining intrasimilarity of the objects. Here it deals with the big datasets consisting of multiple features. Thanks to the developments in IT industry the computation procedure became easy and lead us to easily use clustering and utilize data in a more efficient way using different types of algorithms. Many experts performing in the fields of statistics, AI, machine learning and Big Data are actively making use of clustering. Here we can mention two specific types of clustering: hierarchical and flat clustering, where each differs depending on the algorithms that it makes use of. In the former one the hierarchy of clusters visualized as a tree of clusters is made, whereas in the latter one we can see the creation of the set of clusters without any transparent structure. The mostly used and popular methods of clustering are: kmeans,Clustering of Large Applications (CLARA), kmedoids and Hierarchical.

Dataset - Student Alcohol Consumption

Here in our dataset we deal with the data on 648 students about their alcohol consumption, from the two separate schools in Portugal, with their age, studytime and other variables like Famrel (family relationship), freetime, goout (time spent outside), Dalc and Walc (Daily and Weekly alcohol consumption), health and absences. The main objective of ours is to cluster the data depending on the similarities in their statistics. The data was retrieved from Kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/student-alcohol-consumption).

alcol = subset(alco, select = c(age, studytime, famrel, freetime, goout, Dalc, Walc, health, absences))

plot(alcol)

Before we go further let us check how good is our dataset to be clustered. Here we use the Hopkins statistic which reflects the clustering tendency of data. The robustness level of clustering of data ranges from 0 (low) to 1 (highest).

alco_a <- hopkins(alcol, nrow(alcol)-1)
cat("Hopkins statistics is",alco_a$H)
## Hopkins statistics is 0.3327563

Even though our Hopkins statistics is 0.33, showing that it is moderately distributed and has no significant clustering feature, we proceed with our analysis of data.

a <- get_dist(alcol, method = "euclidean")
fviz_dist(a, show_labels = F) + labs(title = "Ordered Dissimilarity Matrix (ODS) - For Alcohol consumption")

Above in (ODS) we can see how clusters of data are placed, where red ones are close ones and blue one shows distant observations. Here we can easily distinguish the clusters separated by colors.

Now, another step is to find the optimal number of cluster depending on the level of silhouette statistics, which is between -1 (the most undesirable) and 1 (the most desirable).

d <- fviz_nbclust(alcol,FUNcluster=kmeans, method = "s") + labs(title = "Kmeans")
f <- fviz_nbclust(alcol,FUNcluster=pam, method = "s") + labs(title = "Pam")
g <- fviz_nbclust(alcol,FUNcluster=clara, method = "s") + labs(title = "Clara")

grid.arrange(d, f, g, top = "Desirable amount of clusters")

We can easily notice that the one with the highest silhoutte is the most reliable choice. Thus we optimal number of clusters to find is 2, which will be used from now on.

Next thing is the primary goal of our analysis which is to cluster data accordigly. After applying the algorithms, it seems that the split into two is similar among the methods.

cl_num <- 2

km <- kmeans(alcol, cl_num)
kmp <- fviz_cluster(list(data=alcol, cluster=km$cluster), ellipse.type="convex", geom="point", stand=FALSE, palette="Dark2", ggtheme=theme_minimal()) + labs(title = "Kmeans")+theme(legend.position="bottom") 

pamc <- pam(alcol, cl_num)
pamp <- fviz_cluster(list(data=alcol, cluster=pamc$clustering), ellipse.type="convex", geom="point", stand=FALSE, palette="Dark2", ggtheme=theme_minimal()) + labs(title = "Pam")+theme(legend.position="bottom")

claa <- clara(alcol, cl_num)
claap <- fviz_cluster(list(data = alcol, cluster = claa$clustering),ellipse.type = "convex", geom="point", stand = FALSE, palette = "Dark2", ggtheme = theme_minimal()) + labs(title = "Clara")+theme(legend.position="bottom")

grid.arrange(kmp,pamp,claap,heights=unit(0.8, "npc") , top = "Clustering dataset, clusters = 2")

Below we also have a Silhouette diagram for other two methods, PAM and CLARA, where it seems that CLARA is better, because it has created clusters that are more homogenous inside and heterogeneous outside. The first observations that are the closest to the center of a cluster have high silhouettes, and those that lie far from the center have small or even negative silhouettes. It clearly be seen that the CLARA is better in the aspect of differentiation due to the homogeneity and heterogeneity.

slh_pam <- fviz_silhouette(pamc) + labs(title = "PAM")
##   cluster size ave.sil.width
## 1       1  281          0.11
## 2       2  368          0.49
slh_claa <- fviz_silhouette(claa) + labs(title = "CLARA")
##   cluster size ave.sil.width
## 1       1   31          0.41
## 2       2   13          0.23
grid.arrange(slh_pam,slh_claa,top = "Silhouette visualization for 2 clusters")

Dendogram clustering

Here we have the hierarchical type of clustering where we can notice the creation of the hierarchy of clusters. In our dataset we have the hierarhy of a second level. But it becomes highly unreadable after 4th level.

dst <- dist(alcol, method = "euclidean")
res <- hclust(dst, method = "ward.D" )
total <- cutree(res, k = 2)
plot(res, cex = 0.6) 
rect.hclust(res, k = 2, border = c('red','blue'))

Boxplot distribution

Below we can see the distribution of data, especially the median and the spread of data that we possess. We can see that both of the clusters are more or less distributed in the same way, but still the first one looks distributed in a more favorable way.

groupBWplot(alcol, as.factor(total), alpha=0.05)
## Warning in data.frame(..., check.names = FALSE): row names were found from

Final conclusion

For assessment of our analysis we make use of clValid funtion (Cluster Validation technique). Where we have Dunn, Silhouette and Connectivity indexes. Dunn index reflects the goodness of clustering where the maximal distance and minimal distance between clusters is related. Unfortunately it is highly sensitive to the outliers since its calculation is based on the maximum and minimum numbers in the dataset. Connectivity instead measures the uniformity of the structure of clusters, measuring the variance between cluster. The higher the values of these indexes the better the method.

analyse <- clValid(alcol, nClust = 2:4, clMethods = c("hierarchical", "kmeans", "pam", "clara","fanny"), validation = "internal",maxitems = 1000 )

As we can see the best method to use is hierarchical one since we have the highest values for all three indexes. In our case of analysing the data set, hierarchical way of clustering was the best one which reflects that the dendograms should be used to cluster such data. After going through all steps of analyzing the data and clustering we can see how deep in fact is the procedure of clustering and how signifact role it plays in identifying the reliable clusters. Moreover, it was proved not only with numbers but also with graphs and figures through which we grasped the transparency of the clusters.
